\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Whereas, damage resulting from parole officer's testimony at state habea
s proceeding was protected by absolute immunity, because as a witness, the parole officer directly serves the court.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Mee v. Ortega, 967 F.2d 423 (10th Cir. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Subsection (6)(c) of this section does not negate or change the general 
rule for applying presentence confinement credit set forth in \'a7 18-1.3-405,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  which provides that a defendant receive presentence confinement credit on his or her original senten
ce and not on the new sentence. Rather, the filing of a parole revocation complaint merely provides jurisdiction to the parole board, but once the parole board makes its decision, the time starts running again from the date of the complaint whether the c
omplaint is dismissed or parole is revoked. People v. Wallin, 167 P.3d 183 (Colo. App. 2007).
\par }\pard \s18 \qc\sb180 {\*\bkmkstart 17-000003}{\*\bkmkend 17-000003}{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub II. ARREST AND INVESTIGATION OF PAROLEE.
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Parolees, as a class, pose a greater threat of criminal activity to law 
enforcement authorities than ordinary citizens.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  People v. Anderson, 189 Colo. 34, 536 P.2d 302 (1975).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The parole authority must be vested with the power to investigate a paro
lee}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  to ascertain whether a parole violation has occurred if it is to fulfill its statutory function. People v. Anderson, 189 Colo. 34, 536 P.2d 302 (1975).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The police officer does not have the broad power to supervise parolees t
hat is granted to parole officers.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  People v. Anderson, 189 Colo. 34, 536 P.2d 302 (1975).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub A parole officer may cause a police officer to accompany him when a sear
ch is being made.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  People v. Anderson, 189 Colo. 34, 536 P.2d 302 (1975).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The fact that a person is on parole does not justify a search without a 
warrant by any law enforcement officer, other than a parole officer.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  People v. Anderson, 189 Colo. 34, 536 P.2d 302 (1975).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Presence of reasonable cause eliminates need for warrant.}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  A parole officer who is investigating a parole violation is required to have reasonable grounds to believe that a parole violation has occurred. Under these circumstances, when he conducts h
is search in connection with that investigation, the need for a search warrant is eliminated. People v. Anderson, 189 Colo. 34, 536 P.2d 302 (1975) (decided prior to the enactment of \'a7 17-2-201 (5)(f)(I)(D)).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Unrelated evidence admissible in prosecution of another crime.}{\b0\i0
\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Evidence seized within the scope of a reasonable search by a parole officer, even though unrelated to the parole violation, is admissible in the prosecution of another crime. People v. A
nderson, 189 Colo. 34, 536 P.2d 302 (1975).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Arrest ends constructive custody.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0
\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The arrest of a parolee for an alleged violation of the conditions of his parole results in a transposition from constructive to physical custody of such parolee. Schooley v. Wilson, 150 Colo. 483, 374 P.2d 353 (1962)
.
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Section limits period of imprisonment, not authority of board to act.}{
\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The time limitations contained in this section do not limit or prescribe the time within which the parole board must act in order to properly suspend or revoke one's parole. Such t
ime limitations only fix the maximum period of time a suspected parole violator may be held in jail by the parole authorities while they investigate his activities and determine what action should be taken. Folks v. Patterson, 159 Colo. 403, 412 P.2d 214
 (1966); Mora v. Patterson, 370 F.2d 923 (10th Cir. 1967); Goetz v. Gunter, 830 P.2d 1154 (Colo. App. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Thus, board may revoke parole after 15 [now 30] days.}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The contention that the parole board was deprived of any power to revoke parole once the 15-day [now 30-day] period had passed has been decided adversely, and the supreme court adheres to th
is ruling. Williams v. Patterson, 161 Colo. 259, 421 P.2d 474 (1966).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Actions prior to revocation are moot.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0
\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Once the parole board has revoked one's parole, the fact that such person prior to such revocation may have been held for more than the period permitted by this section is of no moment. Folks v. Patterson, 15
9 Colo. 403, 412 P.2d 214 (1966).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Questions with respect to matters transpiring prior to the time a parolee is transferred to the state penitentiary are not justiciable after the t
ransfer. Mora v. Patterson, 370 F.2d 923 (10th Cir. 1967).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Habeas corpus is the remedy for an unlawful restraint}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  of one's liberty under this section as well as for an unlawful imprisonment, and a person on parole can resort to the remedy of habeas corpus where parole officers are not following the mand
ate of this section in regard to revocatory proceedings. Schooley v. Wilson, 150 Colo. 483, 374 P.2d 353 (1962).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Where a parolee was arrested and held in actual custody more than 15 [now 30] days without release or revocation of his parole in violation of thi
s section, habeas corpus was the proper remedy. Schooley v. Wilson, 150 Colo. 483, 374 P.2d 353 (1962).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Habeas corpus will lie where a parolee was being detained by the authorities for a time longer than that permitted by this section prior to the pa
role board's alternative action of either releasing him or revoking his parole. Johnson v. Tinsley, 157 Colo. 539, 404 P.2d 159 (1965).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Relief is discharge only prior to revocation.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0
\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The proviso now appearing in this section that no parolee shall be kept in jail by the division of parole for a period of more than 15 [now 30] days means that a suspected parole violator who is held i
n jail for more than 15 [now 30] days while his activities are being investigated is entitled to relief by way of habeas corpus, the relief being discharge-not from the penitentiary or institution following revocation-but from the institution to which co
nfined prior to revocation. People ex rel. Patterson v. District Court, 159 Colo. 142, 410 P.2d 630 (1966).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Since subsection (4)(a) does not expressly require the county to accept 
"technical" parole violators}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  and evidence existed to show the county jail was overcrowded, the county had no obligation to accept such parole violators. State for Use of Dept. of 
Corr. v. Pena, 837 P.2d 210 (Colo. App. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Subsection (1)(e) does not define a city or county's obligation to accep
t technical parole violators.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The State of Colorado, for the Use of the Dept. of Corr. v. Pena, 855 P.2d 805 (Colo. 1993).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Subsection (4)(a) does not mandate that a county or city accept all alle
ged parole violators who are arrested.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The right to arrest and take a parolee to jail for detention does not entail a duty on the part of jails to accept, without discretion, such
 parolees. The State of Colorado, for the Use of the Dept. of Corr. v. Pena, 855 P.2d 805 (Colo. 1993) (decided under law in effect prior to 1990 amendment).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Subsection (11), read in conjunction with \'a7\'a7 17-2-201 (5.5)(d) and
 17-2-102 (8.5), does not require revocation of parole upon an initial positive drug or alcohol testing.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  But parole board had authority to revoke defendant's parole based on a sin
gle drug or alcohol violation when it occurred in a subsequent test. People v. Whidden, 56 P.3d 1201 (Colo. App. 2002), aff'd on other grounds, 78 P.3d 1092 (Colo. 2003).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The substance abuse in the criminal justice system statutes, article 11.
5 of title 16, and this section authorize, but do not require, the board }{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  to revoke parole and return a parolee to the department of corrections based upon a single positive drug 
test that occurs after the baseline test. People v. Whidden, 78 P.3d 1092 (Colo. 2003).
\par }\pard \s18 \qc\sb180 {\*\bkmkstart 17-000004}{\*\bkmkend 17-000004}{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub III. REVOCATION PROCEEDINGS.
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Probable cause hearing required as promptly as convenient.}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Although this section is silent regarding a time limitation within which the probable cause hearing required by subsection (4) must be held, due process requires only that a hearing be condu
cted as "promptly as convenient". Mijares v. Shipley, 197 Colo. 282, 592 P.2d 414 (1979).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Due process requires fairness in revocation hearings.}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Parolees in parole revocation hearings are not entitled to the specifics of due process available to an accused in the first instance, but this in no way negates their right to enjoy due pro
cess as that mandate reflects the right of all persons to inherent fairness in all compulsive processes. Martinez v. Patterson, 429 F.2d 844 (10th Cir. 1970), cert. denied, 402 U.S. 934, 91 S. Ct. 1528, 28 L. Ed.2d 868 (1971).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  While the parolee's liberty cannot be terminated without reason, it does not follow that he is entitled to all of the federal constitutional proce
dures and safeguards guaranteed by the due process clause of the fourteenth amendment. Thus, he is not entitled to a speedy public trial pursuant to the sixth amendment, but is entitled to a fair hearing for the purpose of ascertaining whether or not he 
has violated his parole. Hutchison v. Patterson, 267 F. Supp. 433 (D. Colo. 1967).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The due process clause of the fourteenth amendment of the federal constitution does not generate rights to confrontation, to cross-examination, or
 to compulsory process at parole revocation hearings. Due process does not comprehend the dual rights to witnesses under oath and evidence in conditional release hearings. Firkins v. Colo., 434 F.2d 1232 (10th Cir. 1970).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub This includes right to know charges and hearing free of caprice.}{\b0\i0
\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The right of a prisoner to be heard at a revocation hearing is inviolative; so, too, is the right to know and be specifically informed of the charges and the nature of the evidence again
st him; and, finally, the right to be free from pure caprice on the part of the discretionary authority before whom the proceedings occur. The right to gather and file written statements before the board is an empty right unless parole violators are give
n notice of the charges prior to their hearing before the parole board. Martinez v. Patterson, 429 F.2d 844 (10th Cir. 1970), cert. denied, 402 U.S. 934, 91 S. Ct. 1528, 28 L. Ed.2d 868 (1971).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub There is no federal constitutional right to counsel at a parole revocati
on proceeding.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Wilkerson v. Patterson, 303 F. Supp. 665 (D. Colo. 1969).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  There is no constitutional right to counsel at parole revocation hearings. Firkins v. Colo., 434 F.2d 1232 (10th Cir. 1970).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The denial of the assistance of counsel at a parole revocation hearing was no ground for federal habeas corpus relief. Williams v. Patterson, 389 
F.2d 374 (10th Cir. 1968); Martinez v. Patterson, 429 F.2d 844 (10th Cir. 1970), cert. denied, 402 U.S. 934, 91 S. Ct. 1528, 28 L. Ed.2d 868 (1971).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Failure to appoint counsel under former section did not deny equal prote
ction.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The argument for a federal constitutional right to appointed counsel under the equal protection clause does not apply where the services rendered by a retained counsel are 
slight and not dependent on unique capabilities with which the attorney is endowed by virtue of his legal training. An indigent defendant suffers no substantial disadvantage because an attorney is not made available to him to write letters to the state p
arole board. No invidious discrimination is present and no violation of the equal protection clause has occurred. Wilkerson v. Patterson, 303 F.Supp. 665 (D. Colo. 1969); Martinez v. Patterson, 429 F.2d 844 (10th Cir. 1970), cert. denied, 402 U.S. 934, 9
1 S. Ct. 1528, 28 L. Ed.2d 868 (1971).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Parole revocation reincarceration is not a new sentence. Since the sentencing power of the judiciary is not implicated, there is no separation of 
powers or due process violation. People v. Barber, 74 P.3d 444 (Colo. App. 2003).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub No statutory duty to preserve testimony in parole revocation hearing.}{
\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Neither the state parole board nor an administrative law judge conducting a parole revocation hearing has a statutory duty to preserve the testimony at a parole revocation hearing.
 In fact, such testimony is inadmissible in a criminal proceeding against the parolee based on the offense giving rise to the parole violation. People v. Schrecongost, 796 P.2d 45 (Colo. App. 1990), aff'd, 810 P.2d 1068 (Colo. 1991).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub If a parolee pleads not guilty to a parole violation complaint alleging 
the commission of a crime for which he has not been convicted,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  the authority seeking parole revocation has the burden of establishing beyond a reasonable doubt that the parolee co
mmitted the alleged offense. People v. White, 804 P.2d 247 (Colo. App. 1990).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Retroactive application of subsection (12) denied under Crim. P. 35(c)(1
)}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  because Crim. P. 35(c)(1) provides a remedy to an offender whose conviction or sentence is affected by a change in the law during the pendency of a direct appeal of such convict
ion or sentence, but not to an offender claiming the benefit of changes in the law that occur during the pendency of other postconviction proceedings. People v. White, 804 P.2d 247 (Colo. App. 1990).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub This section does not limit the amount of time within which the parole b
oard must act}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  on the issue of revocation of parole. Goetz v. Gunter, 830 P.2d 1154 (Colo. App. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The tolling provisions in subsection (6) do not impose additional punish
ment on the parolee.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  If the board determines there was no parole violation, the parolee's status should be reinstated as if no complaint had been filed. Goetz v. Gunter, 830 P.2d 
1154 (Colo. App. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Where a complaint was filed against the parolee near the end of the parole term and the board dismissed the first complaint and brought a second c
omplaint after the parolee's term had expired, the board was without jurisdiction to revoke the parolee's parole based on the second complaint. Goetz v. Gunter, 830 P.2d 1154 (Colo. App. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Tolling of expiration of parole upon the filing of a parole violation co
mplaint does not impose additional punishment and does not violate the prohibition against ex post facto laws.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Goetz v. Gunter, 830 P.2d 1154 (Colo. App. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Rather, it allows the parole board to maintain its jurisdiction over parolee while authorities investigate the alleged parole violations and to ho
ld a revocation hearing. Goetz v. Gunter, 830 P.2d 1154 (Colo. App. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Tolling of expiration of parole upon filing of a parole violation compla
int by parole officer}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  applies to all offenders, including those who committed crimes before the statute was enacted. Duran v. Price, 868 P.2d 375 (Colo. 1994).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The plain meaning of subsection (7) provides that, upon finding good cau
se by the parole board, a parole revocation hearing can be delayed }{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  beyond 30 days after the parolee's arrest and a parolee can be held in custody for a reasonable time pending a 
revocation hearing. The section does not convey automatic good cause to delay a parole hearing for pending resolution of an underlying criminal case, nor does the statute require a parolee to be released from custody after 30 days. Colo. Dept. of Corr. v
. Madison, 85 P.3d 542 (Colo. 2004).
\par }\pard \s8 \qj\sb180\sa180\fi360 {\*\bkmkstart 17-2-103.5}{\*\bkmkend 17-2-103.5}{\b\fs24 17-2-103.5. Revocation proceedings - parolee arrested for certain offenses.
\par }\pard \s9 \qj {\v\fs8 Statute text
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (1) (a) Notwithstanding any provision of section 17-2-103, a community parole officer shall file a complaint seeking revocation of the parole of an
y parolee who:
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (I) Is found in possession of a deadly weapon as defined in section 18-1-901, C.R.S.;
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (II) Is arrested and charged with:
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (A) A felony;
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (B) A crime of violence as defined in section 16-1-104 (8.5), C.R.S.;
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (C) A misdemeanor assault involving a deadly weapon or resulting in bodily injury to the victim;
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (D) Sexual assault in the third degree as defined in section 18-3-404 (2), C.R.S., as it existed prior to July 1, 2000; or
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (E) Unlawful sexual contact as defined in section 18-3-404 (2), C.R.S.
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (b) A community parole officer shall present to the district attorney of the proper judicial district for the purpose of prosecution all the facts 
ascertained by the community parole officer and all other papers, documents, or evidence pertaining thereto that the community parole officer has in his or her possession for any parolee found in possession of a weapon pursuant to section 18-12-108, C.R.
S.
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (c) A hearing relating to such revocation shall be held, unless a board member is advised that a criminal charge is still pending and no technical 
violations are alleged, or where the parolee does not request revocation, in which case the hearing shall be delayed until a disposition concerning the criminal charge is reached.
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (2) If the hearing officer or board member conducting the hearing pursuant to subsection (1) of this section finds the parolee guilty of the conduc
t charged but decides against revoking the parole of the parolee, the record of such hearing shall be reviewed within fifteen days of the decision by two members of the board, exclusive of the board member who conducted the hearing, who may overturn the 
decision and order the parole to be revoked.
