role.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The determinations involved in granting parole depend exclusively on the judgment and discretion of the board. Wilkerson v. Patterson, 174 Colo. 264, 483 P.2d 365 (1971).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The ultimate decision as to the granting or denial of parole is entrusted to the state parole board. Ferchaw v. Tinsley, 234 F. Supp. 922 (D. Colo
. 1964).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The decision of the Colorado state board of parole to grant or deny parole is clearly discretionary since parole is a privilege, and no prisoner i
s entitled to it as a matter of right. In re Question Concerning State Judicial Review, 199 Colo. 463, 610 P.2d 1340 (1980).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The decision to grant parole or absolute release to an inmate incarcerated for an indeterminate sentence under the Colorado Sex Offender Lifetime 
Supervision Act is vested within the sound discretion of the state parole board. The parole board's discretion is plenary and is not subject to judicial review. People v. Oglethorpe, 87 P.3d 129 (Colo. App. 2003).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The parole board must act within scope of delegated authority.}{\b0\i0
\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The parole board is authorized to act only in specified ways. Absolute quasi-judicial immunity to acts not permitted by law does not serve the purpose of more efficient government. Offic
ials who act without the scope of their delegated authority must, at the least, proceed at their own risk. Belveal v. Bray, 253 F. Supp. 606 (D. Colo. 1966).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Decision of the board to deny parole is not an abuse of discretion as lo
ng as there is sufficient evidence before the board to support its decision.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Mulberry v. Neal, 96 F. Supp.2d 1149 (D. Colo. 2000).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub An inmate has a substantial interest in knowing the reason or reasons fr
om the board for denial of parole.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Johnson v. Heggie, 362 F. Supp. 851 (D. Colo. 1973).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub And board must give written reasons.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0
\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Notwithstanding any other policy to the contrary, the board must, by the very terms and conditions of its own rules and regulations, give written reasons for denial or deferral of parole to the inmate concern
ed. Johnson v. Heggie, 362 F. Supp. 851 (D. Colo. 1973).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The general assembly did not intend to provide a mandatory period of par
ole.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Wilkerson v. Patterson, 174 Colo. 264, 483 P.2d 365 (1971).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Board must reconsider application yearly after denial.}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The parole board is explicitly not required to grant an application, but when it does not grant a parole, it must reconsider the application each succeeding year until the prisoner is discha
rged pursuant to law, that is, until he has fully served the maximum term of his sentence less time allowed for good behavior, if any. Wilkerson v. Patterson, 174 Colo. 264, 483 P.2d 365 (1971).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Habeas corpus in the federal district court is not available}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  to secure relief from the decisions of the parole board as to the grant or denial of parole. Ferchaw v. Tinsley, 234 F. Supp. 922 (D. Colo. 1964).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Denial of parole raises no federal question of due process.}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The action of the parole board denying petitioner parole and requiring him to serve the maximum sentence originally imposed by the sentencing court raises no federal question of violation of
 due process or equal protection. Ferchaw v. Tinsley, 234 F. Supp. 922 (D. Colo. 1964).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Restitution as a condition of parole.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0
\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Sentence which ordered defendant to pay restitution as a condition of parole after serving time in prison is consistent with the applicable statutory scheme governing parole and restitution. People v. Martine
z, 734 P.2d 650 (Colo. App. 1987).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The court's duty to fix the amount of restitution is not confined to sen
tences to probation}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  but applies equally to sentences to imprisonment. People v. Johnson, 780 P.2d 504 (Colo. 1989).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub A codefendant is jointly responsible for restitution}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0
\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  when he is also a complicitor in the crime. People v. Fichtner, 869 P.2d 539 (Colo. 1994).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Codefendants were participants and complicitors in the same criminal act
s,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  therefore, each is responsible for the damage he caused and also for the damage caused by the other. People v. Fichtner, 869 P.2d 539 (Colo. 1994).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Where the parole board fails to issue a warrant for the arrest of a paro
lee,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  and the period of parole expires, law enforcement agencies have no authority to arrest the parolee, and the good faith exception and the fellow officer rule do not apply. Peo
ple v. Fields, 785 P.2d 611 (Colo. 1990).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Subsection (5)(a) plainly and unambiguously provides that all habitual c
riminals sentenced pursuant to \'a7 16-13-101 are subject to discretionary parole,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  regardless of when their current offenses were committed. People v. Marquez, 983 P.2d 159 (Colo.
 App. 1999).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Under subsection (5)(a), parole for inmates convicted of sexual offenses
 under \'a7 16-13-202 (5) was discretionary, not mandatory.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Lustgarden v. Kautzky, 811 P.2d 1098 (Colo. 1991); Lustgarden v. Gunter, 779 F. Supp. 500 (D. Colo. 1991); Lustgarden v
. Gunter, 966 F.2d 552 (10th Cir. 1992), cert. denied, 506 U.S. 1008, 113 S. Ct. 624, 121 L.Ed.2d 556 (1992); Jackson v. Zavaras, 963 P.2d 1118 (Colo. App. 1998).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The provisions of \'a7 16-13-216 (1) granting yearly parole consideratio
n for persons sentenced to an indeterminate term pursuant to \'a7 16-13-203 conflict with the provisions of subsection (4)(a) of this section, which allow the parole board to consider parole for sex offenders every three years.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0
\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Since subsection (4)(a) is the later enacted statute, the provisions of subsection (4) prevail. A person sentenced to an indeterminate sentence pursuant to \'a7 16-13-203 is entitled to parole consider
ation only every three years. White v. Van Pelt, 55 P.3d 823 (Colo. App. 2002).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Where defendant was convicted of both a sexual offense and attempted mur
der, and received equal and concurrent sentences for each crime, parole was discretionary pursuant to subsection (5)(a).}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Mahn v. Gunter, 978 F.2d 599 (10th Cir. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub No equal protection violation}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0
\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  where offender convicted of a nonsexual offense would receive mandatory parole, but an offender convicted of a comparable nonsexual offense in which there is an underlying factual basis of unlawful sexual behavior wou
ld receive discretionary parole under subsection (5)(a). Offenders are not similarly situated because different behavior triggers the different parole requirements. People v. Fritschler, 87 P.3d 186 (Colo. App. 2003).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Retroactive application of the parole board's reinterpretation of subsec
tion (5)(a), where the reinterpretation of the ambiguous statutory language was foreseeable,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  did not result in a violation of the ex post facto clause or the due process requireme
nts. Lustgarden v. Gunter, 779 F. Supp. 500 (D. Colo. 1991); Lustgarden v. Gunter, 966 F.2d 552 (10th Cir. 1992), cert. denied, 506 U.S. 1008, 113 S. Ct. 624, 121 L.Ed.2d 556 (1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Because subsection (5)(a) leaves it to the parole board's discretion whe
ther to grant parole before a sex offender completes his sentence,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  petitioner's unilateral belief that good-time credits would result in his early release did not give rise to a c
onstitutionally protected interest. Lustgarden v. Gunter, 779 F. Supp. 500 (D. Colo. 1991); Lustgarden v. Gunter, 966 F.2d 552 (10th Cir. 1992), cert. denied, 506 U.S. 1008, 113 S. Ct. 624, 121 L.Ed.2d 556 (1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Where defendant was convicted of sexually assaulting the victim over a p
eriod of four years that ended July 6, 1998,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  the elements of the crime were not complete, and the crime was not committed, until that date. Therefore, the provisions of subsection
 (5)(a.5) apply and, if the parole board releases the defendant to a period of discretionary parole when he has more than five years of his prison sentence remaining, the length of the parole period may be up to the full amount of the unserved portion of
 his sentence and shall not be subject to the five-year cap. People v. Myers, 45 P.3d 756 (Colo. App. 2001).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Consideration of application for parole is matter entrusted solely to th
e discretion of the parole board}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  for parolee convicted of sexual offenses. White v. People, 866 P.2d 1371 (Colo. 1994).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Court may correct erroneous sentence of person convicted of unlawful sex
ual offense}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  from one-year probation to the period set forth in subsection (5)(a). People v. Reynolds, 907 P.2d 670 (Colo. App. 1995).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Court may correct the mittimus}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0
\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  where the trial court neglected to specify that its sentence included a mandatory period of parole. People v. Mayes, 981 P.2d 1106 (Colo. App. 1999).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Parole decision is subtle and dependent on an amalgam of elements}{\b0
\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  some of which are factual and many of which are purely subjective appraisals by the parole board members based upon their experience. White v. People, 866 P.2d 1371 (Colo. 1994).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Although parole agreement is anticipated, it is not a condition to grant
 of parole but a condition to release on parole.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Regulations do not suggest that grant of parole not effective until prisoner actually released from custody. Prisoner granted paro
le to a county detainer and serving consecutive sentence on another conviction made prima facie case for writ of habeas corpus relief when he alleged that parole had not been suspended or rescinded. Cardiel v. Brittian, 833 P.2d 748 (Colo. 1992) (decided
