\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Since \'a7 17-22.5-203 is similar to repealed \'a7\'a7 17-2-205 and 17-2-206, relevant cases construing those provisions have been included in the annotations to this section.
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Time on parole is not considered to be time which applies against the se
ntence}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  when the parolee is reincarcerated. Ferchaw v. Tinsley, 234 F. Supp. 922 (D. Colo. 1964).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Under this section where a paroled convict returns to prison for violation of his parole, the time between his release on parole and his return to
 prison shall not be taken to be any part of the time served in computing the period to be served under original sentence. Furlow v. Tinsley, 151 Colo. 280, 377 P.2d 132 (1962).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub This statutory refusal to count time spent on parole when sentence is re
sumed does not violate federal due process.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Firkins v. Colo., 434 F.2d 1232 (10th Cir. 1970).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub And is not ground for release on habeas corpus.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0
\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Where petition for habeas corpus contained allegations that petitioner should have been given credit for time served while on parole, his ground for release was improper as a matter of law. Minor v. Ti
nsley, 154 Colo. 249, 389 P.2d 850 (1964).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Statute prohibits awarding credits to parolee against his original sente
nces for time he was later incarcerated}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  awaiting trial on subsequent criminal charges. Santisteven v. Johnson, 751 P.2d 621 (Colo. 1988).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Statute prohibits giving parolee credit for time served prior to his par
ole revocation, while being held on an unrelated charge.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Wiedemer v. People, 784 P.2d 739 (Colo. 1989).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub A parolee is subject to restrictions which are not applicable to other c
itizens.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  People v. Salvador, 189 Colo. 181, 539 P.2d 1273 (1975).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub And he is not free from legal restraint}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0
\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  by the penal authorities, but is constructively a prisoner of the state in the legal custody and under the control of the department of institutions. Schooley v. Wilson, 150 Colo. 483, 374 P.2d 353 (1962).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Release on parole in no way alters the fact that appellant is still unde
r sentence;}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  that he is in technical custody; and that he is under supervision. People v. Salvador, 189 Colo. 181, 539 P.2d 1273 (1975).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Parolee is not in custody of department, for purposes of this section, f
rom time parole detainer is lodged against him,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  where parolee had been arrested and confined for acts of forgery and remained in physical custody of Denver authorities until his p
arole was revoked. Santisteven v. Johnson, 751 P.2d 621 (Colo. 1988).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Tolling of expiration of parole upon the filing of a violation complaint
 does not impose additional punishment on parole violator.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Goetz v. Gunter, 830 P.2d 1154 (Colo. App. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The phrase "return to said custody" refers to the time of parole revocat
ion.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Wiedemer v. People, 784 P.2d 739 (Colo. 1989).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  When a parolee is returned to custody, the time between his or her release and return to custody is not considered part of the term of the sentenc
e. "Return to custody" means the time at which parole is revoked, not the time at which the defendant is reincarcerated. People v. Norton, 49 P.3d 344 (Colo. App. 2001), rev'd on other grounds, 63 P.3d 339 (Colo. 2003).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The probationer has a substantially different status from that of the pa
rolee.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The imposition of sentence in his case has been suspended and thus unlike the parolee he is not serving a sentence while on probation. Hutchison v. Patterson, 267 F. Supp. 
433 (D. Colo. 1967).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Parole does not operate as a discharge.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0
\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  A paroled prisoner who receives a ticket and leaves the prison as provided by this section is not discharged and can later be restrained as a parole violator. Johnson v. Tinsley, 157 Colo. 539, 404 P.2d 159 (
1965) (decided under repealed \'a7 27-20-120).
\par }\pard \s31 \qc {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub \'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\page 
\par }\pard \s6 \qc\sb180\sa180 {\*\bkmkstart t. 17, art. 22.5, p. 3}{\*\bkmkend t. 17, art. 22.5, p. 3}{\b\fs28 PART 3\line OFFENDERS SENTENCED FOR CRIMES\line  COMMITTED ON OR AFTER JULY 1, 1979
\par }\pard \s8 \qj\sb180\sa180\fi360 {\*\bkmkstart 17-22.5-301}{\*\bkmkend 17-22.5-301}{\b\fs24 17-22.5-301. Good time.
\par }\pard \s9 \qj {\v\fs8 Statute text
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (1) Each person sentenced for a crime committed on or after July 1, 1979, but before July 1, 1981, whose conduct indicates that he has substantiall
y observed all of the rules and regulations of the institution or facility in which he has been confined and has faithfully performed the duties assigned to him shall be entitled to a good time deduction of fifteen days a month from his sentence. The goo
d time authorized by this section shall vest quarterly and may not be withdrawn once it has vested. No more than forty-five days of good time may be withheld by the department in any three-month period of sentence.
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (2) Each person sentenced for a crime committed on or after July 1, 1981, but before July 1, 1985, shall be subject to all the provisions of this p
art 3; except that the good time authorized by this section shall vest semiannually and no more than ninety days of good time may be withheld by the department in any six-month period of sentence.
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (3) Each person sentenced for a crime committed on or after July 1, 1985, shall be subject to all the provisions of this part 3; except that the go
od time authorized by this section shall not vest and may be withheld or deducted by the department.
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (4) Nothing in this section shall be so construed as to prevent the department from withholding good time earnable in subsequent periods of sentenc
e, but not yet earned, for conduct occurring in a given period of sentence.
