\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub For crimes committed on or after July 1, 1985, deductions for earned tim
e are within discretionary authority of the department of corrections.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Since the department of corrections may withhold, withdraw, or restore earned time deductions, an inmate's m
aximum control date, as initially calculated by the department of corrections, is not necessarily the date upon which he is entitled to unconditional release. Renneke v. Kautzky, 782 P.2d 343 (Colo. 1989).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Granting of earned time credit for educational programs under subsection
 (1.5) lies with the discretion of the department.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  To read "shall" in subsection (1.5) in a mandatory sense would create an absurd result. An inmate has no clear right to receive 
and department has no clear duty to grant earned time credit. Verrier v. Dept. of Corr., 77 P.3d 875 (Colo. App. 2003).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub An inmate who is incarcerated in the state prison system is eligible for
 two types of time deduction from his sentence.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The first is "good time" pursuant to \'a7 17-22.5-301, which rewards the inmate who substantially observes the rules and regulation
s of the facility in which he is confined and who faithfully performs his assigned duties. The second is "earned time" under this section which is provided if the inmate makes substantial progress in matters such as work and training. Bynum v. Kautzky, 7
84 P.2d 735 (Colo. 1989).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Inmate not entitled to earned time for time spent in county jail}{\b0\i0
\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  because statutory requirements of this section were not met. People v. Alderman, 720 P.2d 1000 (Colo. App. 1986).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Good time and earned time credits do not constitute service of sentence}
{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  and are only used to determine inmate's parole eligibility date. Thorson v. Dept. of Corr., 801 P.2d 540 (Colo. 1990); Myers v. Price, 842 P.2d 229 (Colo. 1992).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Subsection (3) of this section and \'a7\'a7 16-11-310 (now repealed), 17
-22.5-301 (2), and 17-22.5-303 (2) do not preclude the reincarceration of a person for violating his parole}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  even though his time served, together with his good time and earned tim
e credits accrued, equal or exceed the length of the sentence originally imposed. Bynum v. Kautzky, 784 P.2d 735 (Colo. 1989); Williamson v. Jordan, 797 P.2d 744 (Colo. 1990); Jones v. Martinez, 799 P.2d 385 (Colo. 1990).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The earned time and good time provisions of this section and \'a7 17-22.
5-301 do not preclude the reincarceration of an inmate for violation of his parole.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  These sections, together with \'a7 16-11-310 (now repealed), were only intended to establish th
e mandatory date of release on parole. Thus, with respect to parole, the good time and earned time credits "vest" only for the purpose of determining parole eligibility, not for purposes of determining whether reincarceration is possible once a former in
mate has violated his parole. Bynum v. Kautzky, 784 P.2d 735 (Colo. 1989); Williamson v. Jordan, 797 P.2d 744 (Colo. 1990); Jones v. Martinez, 799 P.2d 385 (Colo. 1990).
