\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub It is not a violation of the ex post facto clause}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0
\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  found in article II section 11 of the Colorado Constitution to apply the amendment of this section which requires that parole time not be credited upon a second parole violation to a defendant who viol
ates parole after the effective date of the amendment. Gasper v. Gunter, 851 P.2d 912 (Colo. 1993); People v. Gallegos, 975 P.2d 1135 (Colo. App. 1998).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub 1994 amendments to subsection (6) create only a speculative and attenuat
ed risk of producing the prohibited effect of increasing the actual punishment}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  for the covered crimes. These speculative effects are insufficient to establish a violation of the e
x post facto prohibition. Funari v. Zavaras, 914 P.2d 508 (Colo. App. 1996).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Trial courts do not have the authority to impose a period of parole as p
art of a sentence.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Only the parole board has the authority to determine whether and for what period parole is appropriate. People v. Mendez, 897 P.2d 868 (Colo. App. 1995).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub A defendant is not legally entitled to good time credit,}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  even though he or she may become eligible for such credit. People v. McCreadie, 938 P.2d 528 (Colo. 1997).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub For felonies committed on or after July 1, 1985, good time and earned ti
me credits are within discretionary authority of the department of corrections.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Since the department of corrections may withdraw good time and earned time credits, an inmate's max
imum control date, as initially calculated by the department of corrections, is not necessarily the date upon which he is entitled to unconditional release. Renneke v. Kautzky, 782 P.2d 343 (Colo. 1989).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Only purpose of accumulation of good time credits}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0
\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  is for determining parole eligibility date of inmates and such credits do not constitute service of sentence. People v. Swepston, 822 P.2d 510 (Colo. App. 1991); Myers v. Price, 842 P.2d 229 (Colo. 199
2).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Parole violator reincarcerated for the lesser of two years or the remain
der of sentence originally imposed.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Subsection (2) provides that a parole violator may be returned to the institution in which he was originally received for a period of not more 
than two years, but in no event may the reincarceration and the subsequent term of parole and the sentence actually served exceed the sentence originally imposed. Thus, the parole board's imposition of a two-year term of reincarceration was improper. Peo
ple v. Leedom, 781 P.2d 173 (Colo. App. 1989).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub For purposes of a parole revocation, the term "sentence already served"}
{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  in subsection (2) includes all previous periods of incarceration plus all previous periods of release on parole. People v. Browning, 809 P.2d 1086 (Colo. App. 1990).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Effect of parole violation on discretion to impose sentence to be served
 concurrently or consecutively.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Even though a parolee could be reincarcerated after parole revocation for a maximum period of only six months, for the purposes of sentencing for a
 subsequent offense committed while on parole, the parolee was reincarcerated for the original offense. Therefore, the court sentencing for the subsequent offense had the discretion to impose the sentence to run consecutively to the period of reincarcera
tion. People v. Lucero, 772 P.2d 58 (Colo. 1989).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Subsection (2) of this section and \'a7\'a7 16-11-310 (now repealed), 17
-22.5-301 (2), and 17-22.5-302 (3) do not preclude the reincarceration of a person for violating his parole}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  even though his time served, together with his good time and earned tim
e credits accrued, equal or exceed the length of the sentence originally imposed. Bynum v. Kautzky, 784 P.2d 735 (Colo. 1989); Williamson v. Jordan, 797 P.2d 744 (Colo. 1990); Jones v. Martinez, 799 P.2d 385 (Colo. 1990).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Although the legislature revised and relocated the good time, earned tim
e, and parole provisions originally included \'a7 16-11-310 (now repealed),}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  eventually moving them to their present location in the statutes at \'a7\'a7 17-22.5-301 to 17-22.5-303
, there is nothing in those revisions which would indicate that \'a7 16-11-310 was meant to render inoperative the provision in this section allowing reincarceration for a parole violation. Such an interpretation is unjustified since it would severely un
dermine the ability of the parole system to effect the successful reintegration of former inmates into the community while recognizing the need for public safety. Bynum v. Kautzky, 784 P.2d 735 (Colo. 1989).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Plain and clear language of this section}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0
\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  requires that a parole violator not be reincarcerated for a period in excess of the balance of time to be served on such person's original sentence and that good time credits acquired during reincarceration b
e applied in a manner that will not so extend the balance of such person's original sentence. Anderson v. Kautzky, 786 P.2d 1082 (Colo. 1989).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Credits may not be carried forward.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0
\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Good time and earned time credits received during original period of incarceration do not apply to period of reincarceration. Williamson v. Jordan, 797 P.2d 744 (Colo. 1990); Jones v. Martinez, 799 P.2d 385 (
Colo. 1990).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Good time and earned time credits cannot be used to diminish defendant's
 sentence and accelerate release date.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  People v. Grenemyer, 827 P.2d 603 (Colo. App. 1992) (decided under section as it existed prior to its repeal in 1988).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub It was foreseeable that \'a7 16-11-310 would not be construed in such ma
nner as to defeat the purpose or eliminate the requirement of parole.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The possibility of reincarceration for violating conditions of parole necessarily rejects the concept of an i
ncarcerated person meriting diminution of sentence by credits for good behavior prior to being released on a conditional basis. People v. Grenemyer, 827 P.2d 603 (Colo. App. 1992) (decided under section as it existed prior to its repeal in 1988); Fultz v
. Embry, 158 F.3d 1101 (10th Cir. 1998).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Inmate who was eligible for mandatory parole under the longest of three 
concurrent sentences imposed upon him}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  was entitled to be released on parole. Vaughn v. Gunter, 820 P.2d 659 (Colo. 1991).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Parole board has authority to impose parole on inmates who committed off
enses between July 1, 1984, and July 1, 1985,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  pursuant to subsection (4) regardless of whether sentencing court imposed illegal sentence by imposing period of parole. People v. Sw
epston, 822 P.2d 510 (Colo. App. 1991).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub In determining a defendant's parole date where consecutive sentences hav
e been imposed and both the mandatory and discretionary parole statutes apply,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  the court should construe the consecutive sentences as one continuous sentence. The defendant's righ
t to mandatory parole under the first conviction is nullified by his two subsequent discretionary parole convictions. Spoto v. Colo. State Dept. of Corr., 883 P.2d 11 (Colo. 1994); People v. Gallegos, 975 P.2d 1135 (Colo. App. 1998); Badger v. Suthers, 9
85 P.2d 1042 (Colo. 1999).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Department of corrections acted properly}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0
\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  when it combined all of defendant's sentences, treating them as a continuous sentence, before the applicable parole date was determined. People v. Gallegos, 975 P.2d 1135 (Colo. App. 1998).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub When a defendant is paroled under this section or under \'a7 17-22.5-403
, he must be reincarcerated for a parole violation under the same statute.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  People v. Gallegos, 975 P.2d 1135 (Colo. App. 1998).
\par }\pard \s8 \qj\sb180\sa180\fi360 {\*\bkmkstart 17-22.5-303.3}{\*\bkmkend 17-22.5-303.3}{\b\fs24 17-22.5-303.3. Violent offenders - parole.
\par }\pard \s9 \qj {\v\fs8 Statute text
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (1) Any person sentenced for second degree murder, first degree assault, first degree kidnapping, unless the first degree kidnapping is a class 1 f
elony, first or second degree sexual assault, first degree arson, first degree burglary, or aggravated robbery, committed on or after July 1, 1987, who has previously been convicted of a crime of violence, shall be eligible for parole after he has served
 seventy-five percent of the sentence imposed less any time authorized for earned time pursuant to section 17-22.5-302. Thereafter, the provisions of section 17-22.5-303 (6) and (7) shall apply.
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (2) Any person sentenced for any crime enumerated in subsection (1) of this section, who has twice previously been convicted for a crime of violenc
e, shall be eligible for parole after he has served the sentence imposed less any time authorized for earned time pursuant to section 17-22.5-302. Thereafter, the provisions of section 17-22.5-303 (6) and (7) shall apply.
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub (3) The governor may grant parole to an offender to whom this section applies before such offender's parole eligibility date if, in the governor's 
opinion, extraordinary mitigating circumstances exist and such offender's release from institutional custody is compatible with the safety and welfare of society.
