\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Annotator's note.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1
\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Since \'a7 17-26-102 is identical to repealed \'a7 27-26-102, relevant cases construing that provision have been included in the annotations to this section.
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub General powers of county commissioners yield to special powers of sherif
f in reference to jails.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  General powers conferred upon the board of county commissioners with respect to county property, when in conflict with the special, particular powers conf
erred upon the sheriff with reference to jails, must yield to the latter. Richart v. Bd. of County Comm'rs, 95 Colo. 153, 33 P.2d 971 (1934).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Hence, sheriff may determine use of particular rooms.}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  It is for the sheriff to determine whether or not a particular room or some other place in the jail should be used for cleaning and conference purposes. The county commissioners have no auth
ority to forbid the sheriff to occupy a vacant room as a living room. Richart v. Bd. of County Comm'rs, 95 Colo. 153, 33 P.2d 971 (1934).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub For various powers and duties of sheriff as jailer,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0
\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  see Richart v. Bd. of County Comm'rs, 95 Colo. 153, 33 P.2d 971 (1934).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub A jailer cannot perform satisfactorily the duties imposed upon him by la
w without living in the jail.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  To accomplish the best results, he should be present night and day to control and guard the prisoners, repel attacks, prevent escapes and forcible ja
il deliveries, feed the prisoners, and minister to those that are sick and might need constant attention. Richart v. Bd. of County Comm'rs, 95 Colo. 153, 33 P.2d 971 (1934).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Therefore it is customary and proper for the jailer to live in the jail,
}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  and this custom is recognized by Colorado statutes. Richart v. Bd. of County Comm'rs, 95 Colo. 153, 33 P.2d 971 (1934).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub However, there is no statute specifically requiring the jailer to live i
n the jail;}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  but the instant section recognizes the existence and propriety of the custom. Richart v. Bd. of County Comm'rs, 95 Colo. 153, 33 P.2d 971 (1934).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub This section does not authorize living quarters in the jail or a housing
 allowance in lieu thereof,}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  either as partial compensation or salary for a sheriff jailer. Van Cleave v. Bd. of County Comm'rs, 33 Colo. App. 227, 518 P.2d 1371 (1973).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub County may provide living quarters under certain circumstances.}{\b0\i0
\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  County is not prohibited from providing living quarters to a jailer where public purposes can be achieved thereby. Van Cleave v. Bd. of County Comm'rs, 33 Colo. App. 227, 518 P.2d 1371 (
1973).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Elimination of housing allowance was constitutional.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0
\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Because housing allowance paid to sheriff jailer was unauthorized and illegal, its elimination did not violate constitutional prohibitions against salary or compensation reduction during the term of
 office of a public official. But the decision holding such payments illegal and unauthorized would not be applied retroactively, and, therefore, a county could not recover for sums already paid to sheriff for such allowance. Van Cleave v. Bd. of County 
Comm'rs, 33 Colo. App. 227, 518 P.2d 1371 (1973).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The sheriff may perform the duties of keeper personally or by deputy.}{
\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  But there is no law which entitles him to special or extra compensation for such services. Bd. of County Comm'rs v. Bransom, 4 Colo. App. 274, 35 P. 750 (1894).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Keeping jail in good order and repair is county expense.}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The expense of keeping the jail in good order and repair, and of lighting and warming the part where the prisoners are confined, must be paid by the county; but the liability of the county i
s on account of expense, and not of service. Bd. of County Comm'rs v. Bransom, 4 Colo. App. 274, 35 P. 750 (1894).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub For action for damages for death of person confined in jail,}{\b0\i0\ul0
\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  see People ex rel. Coover v. Guthner, 105 Colo. 37, 94 P.2d 699 (1939).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Applied}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0
\nosupersub  in Tihonovich v. Williams, 196 Colo. 144, 582 P.2d 1051 (1978).
\par }\pard \s8 \qj\sb180\sa180\fi360 {\*\bkmkstart 17-26-103}{\*\bkmkend 17-26-103}{\b\fs24 17-26-103. Duties of keeper.
\par }\pard \s9 \qj {\v\fs8 Statute text
\par }\pard \s29 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f0\fs24\cf0\nosupersub The keepers of the several county jails and adult detention centers in this state shall receive and safely keep every person duly committed or plac
ed pursuant to section 16-11-308.5, C.R.S., to such jail or adult detention center for safekeeping, examination, or trial or duly sentenced to imprisonment in such jail or adult detention center upon conviction for any contempt or misconduct or for any c
riminal offense, and they shall not without lawful authority let out of such jail, on bail or otherwise, any such person.
\par }\pard \s9 \qj {\v\fs8 History
