\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Since \'a7 17-27-106 is similar to \'a7 17-27-108 as it existed prior to the 1993 repeal and reenactment of this article, relevant cases construing those provisions have been included in the annotations to this section.
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Section applies to work release facilities.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0
\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  This section covers both traditional penitentiary type institutions operated by the state department of corrections and less traditional correctional facilities such as work release facilities. People 
v. Lucero, 654 P.2d 835 (Colo. 1982).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  The failure to return to a work release facility upon the expiration of a 10-hour pass is punishable as escape under \'a7 18-8-208. People v. Luce
ro, 654 P.2d 835 (Colo. 1982).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Leaving a community corrections facility without authorization}{\b0\i0
\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  constitutes escape under \'a7 18-8-208 because offender is still in custody and subject to the authority of the court. People v. Brown, 695 P.2d 776 (Colo. App. 1984).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Person who absconds from a non-residential community corrections placeme
nt commits the crime of escape in violation of this section and \'a7 18-8-208.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  By its plain language, the section applies to all types of community corrections placements, includi
ng non-residential community corrections programs. People v. Forester, 1 P.3d 758 (Colo. App. 2000).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub A parolee may be convicted of escape even if there is a legal defect in 
the process of confinement.}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  Such defects are to be challenged through appropriate legal means rather than through unauthorized departure from a custodial facility. People v. Lanzi
eri, 25 P.3d 1170 (Colo. 2001).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub Delegating supervisory power to probation department and community corre
