 App. 2003); People v. Sa'ra, 117 P.3d 51 (Colo. App. 2004).
\par }\pard \s17 \qj\sb180\fi360 {\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  }{\b\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub The court did not err in instructing the jury under this section concern
ing custody or confinement}{\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\v0\expnd0\expndtw0\outl0\shad0\f1\fs20\cf0\nosupersub  where, taken together, the jury instructions, the information, and the parole mittimus signed by defendant indicate that he had sufficient notice that h
e could be liable for escape from custody. People v. Taylor, 74 P.3d 396 (Colo. App. 2002).
